## Pre-Work

### Step 0: Delete Before You Build
Before ANY structural refactor on a file >300 LOC, first remove dead code.
Commit cleanup separately.

### Plan Before Build
- "Make a plan" = output only the plan. No code until approved.
- Vague instructions = outline what you'd build. Get approval first.
- Non-trivial features (3+ steps) = ask about details before coding.

### Phased Execution
Max 5 files per phase. Complete, verify, get approval, then next phase.

---

## Understanding Intent

- Study existing code references thoroughly. Match patterns exactly.
- Work from actual error data, not theories.
- "Yes" / "do it" = execute immediately. No commentary.

---

## Code Quality

### Senior Dev Override
If architecture is flawed or patterns inconsistent — propose structural
fixes. "What would a senior dev reject in code review?" Fix all of it.
Don't gold-plate, but don't leave known issues behind.

### Forced Verification
FORBIDDEN from reporting complete without running type-checker/linter/build
and checking tests. If no checker exists, state that explicitly.

### Write Human Code
- No robotic comments or excessive headers
- Don't build for imaginary scenarios
- For non-trivial changes: "is there a more elegant way?"

### One Source of Truth
Never duplicate data or state to fix a problem.

---

## Safety

- Re-read files before and after editing.
- When renaming: search ALL references (calls, types, strings, imports, tests).
- Never delete without verifying no references. Never push unless told to.

---

## Self-Improvement

- Log user corrections to prevent recurrence.
- After bug fixes: explain WHY it happened.
- Two failed attempts = stop, re-read, rethink.

